I have everything I need. The snapshot has confirmed the full `proxy.ts` file, the `next.config.ts`, and the `package.json`. Let me give you a thorough diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

There are **two independent bugs** working together to completely bypass your auth check for `/api/internal/*`. Neither one alone would explain the full breakage, but both existed before the Next.js 16 upgrade — the upgrade simply hardened the rules in a way that made both bugs bite simultaneously.

---

## Root Cause

### Bug 1 — The proxy is named wrong and is never invoked as middleware (primary cause)

Next.js Middleware has a strict **file-name and export contract**. The runtime looks for **exactly one file** at the project root (or `src/`) named `middleware.ts` / `middleware.js`, and it must export a function called `export default` (or `export { middleware }`). Your file is named `proxy.ts` and exports a named function called `proxy`.

```
src/proxy.ts          ← ❌  wrong filename
export function proxy  ← ❌  wrong export name
export const config    ← the matcher here is never read because
                          Next.js never treats this file as middleware
```

In Next.js 15 this may have appeared to work if something else (a now-removed `middleware.ts`, or a module that manually imported and called `proxy()`) wired it up. After the upgrade that implicit shim is gone. **No `middleware.ts` file exists** in the snapshot (`src/middleware.ts` → ENOENT), which confirms the function is simply never called.

### Bug 2 — The allow-list inside `proxy()` already punches a hole through all of `/api` (secondary cause)

Even if the file were named correctly, there is an overly broad early-return inside the guard:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts  (line 13-15)
if (pathname.startsWith("/admin") || pathname.startsWith("/api")) {
  return NextResponse.next();   // ← unconditionally passes ALL /api/* routes
}
```

This means `/api/internal/anything` is explicitly whitelisted. The comment says *"Payload has its own auth"*, which is true for `/api/payload/*` but **not** for your own `/api/internal/*` routes.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Rename and re-export the file as a proper Next.js middleware

Create `src/middleware.ts` (delete / deprecate `src/proxy.ts`):

```ts
// src/middleware.ts
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
import { verifySessionValue, COOKIE_NAME } from "@/lib/company-session";

// ─── route classification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/** Routes that Payload CMS owns — it manages its own auth layer. */
function isPayloadRoute(pathname: string) {
  return (
    pathname.startsWith("/admin") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/api/payload") // Payload's own API namespace
  );
}

/** Public entry-points that must be reachable without a session. */
function isPublicRoute(pathname: string) {
  return (
    pathname.startsWith("/for/") ||
    pathname === "/for" ||
    pathname.startsWith("/_next/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/images/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/media/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/videos/") ||
    pathname === "/favicon.ico" ||
    pathname === "/robots.txt" ||
    pathname === "/sitemap.xml"
  );
}

// ─── middleware entry-point ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = request.nextUrl;

  if (isPayloadRoute(pathname) || isPublicRoute(pathname)) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Everything else — including /api/internal/* — requires a valid session.
  const sessionCookie = request.cookies.get(COOKIE_NAME)?.value;
  if (!sessionCookie) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const company = verifySessionValue(sessionCookie);
  if (!company) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const requestHeaders = new Headers(request.headers);
  requestHeaders.set("x-company", company);

  return NextResponse.next({
    request: { headers: requestHeaders },
  });
}

// ─── matcher ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    /*
     * Match every path EXCEPT the static-asset prefixes Next.js itself
     * handles before middleware runs. Keeping this tight avoids the
     * overhead of running session verification on every image/font byte.
     */
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|sitemap.xml|robots.txt).*)",
  ],
};
```

### Step 2 — Verify your Payload API namespace

Open your `src/payload.config.ts` and confirm (or set) the `routes.api` value:

```ts
// src/payload.config.ts
export default buildConfig({
  routes: {
    admin: "/admin",
    api:   "/api/payload",   // ← scope Payload's API to its own prefix
  },
  // ...
});
```

If `routes.api` is left at the Payload default of `/api`, its endpoints collide with your own `/api/internal/*` routes and you cannot distinguish them in middleware. Give Payload its own prefix once and the `isPayloadRoute` guard above becomes perfectly precise.

### Step 3 — Delete the old file

```bash
git rm src/proxy.ts
```

If any other module imported `proxy` for manual use, replace those call-sites — middleware cannot and should not be called as a regular function.

---

## Principle

> **Next.js Middleware is a framework contract, not a utility function.**

The runtime discovers middleware solely by filename (`middleware.ts` at the project root or inside `src/`) and export shape (`export default` or `export { middleware }`). A correctly written guard function in a file with any other name is completely invisible to the router — it will never run, regardless of how perfect its `config.matcher` is. This is the core failure mode here: the auth logic was sound, but it was dead code because the file was never loaded as middleware.

The secondary lesson is **never write a blanket `pathname.startsWith("/api")` pass-through** when only a subset of routes (`/api/payload/*`) actually need it. Favour explicit prefixes that match exactly the namespace you intend to delegate to a downstream auth layer.
